{"result": "{\n    \"title\": \"Chapter X: Residual Income and Investment Decisions\",\n    \"summary\": \"Chapter X delves into the concept of Residual Income (RI) and its application in assessing the profitability of investments and divisions within a company. The chapter covers the calculation of RI, which involves deducting imputed interest from the net profit. Key examples include the Gearbox Division Capital Equipment Investment and the Plastics Division\u2019s Residual Income, which illustrate the practical application of RI in real-world scenarios. The chapter also explores the relationship between RI and other financial metrics such as controllable profit and return on investment (ROI).\",\n    \"rating\": 8.5,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact severity rating is high due to the critical role of residual income in investment decision-making and performance assessment.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Residual Income (RI) is a key metric for assessing profitability.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Residual Income (RI) is calculated as the net profit after deducting an imputed interest charge on the capital employed. It is used to assess the profitability of an investment or division, as well as the performance of divisions within a company. RI represents the income that remains after subtracting the imputed interest charge on capital employed from the controllable profit [Data: Concepts (1184); Relationships (1182, 1166, 1161)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Imputed interest is crucial in the calculation of Residual Income.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Imputed interest is a notional interest charge calculated on the capital employed by the head office. It is determined by multiplying the capital employed by the interest rate. This imputed interest is used in the calculation of residual income, where it is subtracted from the controllable profit to determine the RI [Data: Concepts (1175); Relationships (1166, 1161)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"The Gearbox Division Capital Equipment Investment example illustrates the application of RI.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The Gearbox division is considering investing in capital equipment costing $2.7m with an expected useful economic life of 50 years and no resale value. The forecast return on the initial investment is 15% per year before depreciation, and the division's cost of capital is 7%. The expected annual residual income of the initial investment is calculated to be $162,000. This example demonstrates how RI can be used to evaluate the profitability of a significant capital investment [Data: Concepts (1958); Relationships (1180)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"The Plastics Division\u2019s Residual Income example provides a detailed calculation.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The quiz question asks what is the plastic division\u2019s residual income given the following data: The plastics division of Ladmar has just reported a divisional return on capital employed of 30% for the last 12 months. The capital employed in the plastics division is $1,200,000. The company\u2019s overall return on capital employed is 18%, and the overall cost of capital is 14%. The plastics division\u2019s cost of capital is 13%. The correct answer is C. The divisional profit is $1.2m * 30% = $360,000. Imputed interest is $1.2m * 13% = $156,000. Therefore, residual income = $360,000 \u2212 $156,000 = $204,000 [Data: Concepts (1304); Relationships (1179)].\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Residual Income is linked to other financial metrics.\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Residual income is closely related to other financial metrics such as controllable profit and return on investment (ROI). For instance, RI is calculated using controllable profit, subtracting the imputed interest on capital employed. This relationship highlights the interconnecte